ABSTRACT
Near-field radiative heat transfer has been a subject of great interest due to the applicability to thermal management and energy conversion. In this letter, a submicron gap between a pair of diced fused quartz substrates is formed by using micromachined low-density pillars to obtain both the parallelism and small parasitic heat conduction. The gap uniformity is validated by the optical interferometry at four corners of the substrates. The heat flux across the gap is measured in a steady-state and is no greater than twice of theoretically predicted radiative heat flux, which indicates that the parasitic heat conduction is suppressed to the level of the radiative heat transfer or less. The heat conduction through the pillars is modeled, and it is found to be limited by the thermal contact resistance between the pillar top and the opposing substrate surface. The methodology to form and evaluate the gap promotes the near-field radiative heat transfer to various applications such as thermal rectification, thermal modulation, and thermophotovoltaics.
Radiative heat transfer between two materials placed in the near-field regime is known to exceed the blackbody limit. 1 1. D. Polder and M. Van Hove, Phys. Rev. B 4 , 3303 (1971). https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevB.4.3303 Such radiative heat transfer behaves as quasi-monochromatic when materials support the electromagnetic surface resonances. Theoretical studies have reported the near field thermal radiation based on a parallel-plate geometry for numbers of applications, i.e., thermophotovoltaics, 2–5 2. A. Narayanaswamy and G. Chen, Appl. Phys. Lett. 82 , 3544 (2003). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.1575936 3. M. Laroche, R. Carminati, and J.-J. Greffet, J. Appl. Phys. 100 , 063704 (2006). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.2234560 4. K. Park, S. Basu, W. P. King, and Z. M. Zhang, J. Quant. Spectrosc. Radiat. Transfer 109 , 305 (2008). https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jqsrt.2007.08.022 5. M. Francoeur, R. Vaillon, and M. P. Menguc, IEEE Trans. Energy Convers. 26 , 686 (2011). https://doi.org/10.1109/TEC.2011.2118212 thermal rectification, 6–11 6. C. R. Otey, W. T. Lau, and S. Fan, Phys. Rev. Lett. 104 , 154301 (2010). https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.104.154301 7. S. Basu and M. Francoeur, Appl. Phys. Lett. 98 , 113106 (2011). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.3567026 8. H. Iizuka and S. Fan, J. Appl. Phys. 112 , 024304 (2012). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.4737465 9. L. P. Wang and Z. M. Zhang, Nanoscale Microscale Thermophys. Eng. 17 , 337 (2013). https://doi.org/10.1080/15567265.2013.776154 10. Y. Yang, S. Basu, and L. Wang, Appl. Phys. Lett. 103 , 163101 (2013). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.4825168 11. H. Iizuka and S. Fan, J. Quant. Spectrosc. Radiat. Transfer 148 , 156– 164 (2014). https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jqsrt.2014.07.007 thermal switch, 12 12. L. Zhu, C. R. Otey, and S. Fan, Appl. Phys. Lett. 100 , 044104 (2012). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.3679694 thermal modulation, 13–15 13. S. A. Biehs, F. S. S. Rosa, and P. Ben-Abdallah, Appl. Phys. Lett. 98 , 243102 (2011). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.3596707 14. L. Cui, Y. Huang, J. Wang, and K. Y. Zhu, Appl. Phys. Lett. 102 , 053106 (2013). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.4790292 15. Y. Huang, S. V. Boriskina, and G. Chen, Appl. Phys. Lett. 105 , 244102 (2014). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.4904456 and thermal transistor, 16 16. P. Ben-Abdallah and S. A. Biehs, Phys. Rev. Lett. 112 , 044301 (2014). https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.112.044301 in which large heat flux and/or spectral coherence are adopted.
On the experimental side, a sphere-plate geometry 17–24 17. A. Narayanaswamy, S. Shen, and G. Chen, Phys. Rev. B 78 , 115303 (2008). https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevB.78.115303 18. S. Shen, A. Narayanaswamy, and G. Chen, Nano Lett. 9 , 2909 (2009). https://doi.org/10.1021/nl901208v 19. E. Rousseau, A. Siria, G. Jourdan, S. Volz, F. Comin, J. Chevrier, and J.-J. Greffet, Nat. Photonics 3 , 514 (2009). https://doi.org/10.1038/nphoton.2009.144 20. P. J. van Zwol, L. Ranno, and J. Chevrier, Phys. Rev. Lett. 108 , 234301 (2012). https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.108.234301 21. B. Guha, C. Otey, C. B. Poitras, S. Fan, and M. Lipson, Nano Lett. 12 , 4546 (2012). https://doi.org/10.1021/nl301708e 22. S. Shen, A. Narayanaswamy, S. Goh, and G. Chen, Appl. Phys. Lett. 92 , 063509 (2008). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.2829999 23. J. Shi, P. Li, B. Liu, and S. Shen, Appl. Phys. Lett. 102 , 183114 (2013). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.4804631 24. J. Shi, B. Liu, P. Li, L. Y. Ng, and S. Shen, Nano Lett. 15 , 1217– 1221 (2015). https://doi.org/10.1021/nl504332t and integrated nanobeams 25 25. R. St-Gelais, B. Guha, L. Zhu, S. Fan, and M. Lipson, Nano Lett. 14 , 6971 (2014). https://doi.org/10.1021/nl503236k have been utilized to achieve excellent agreement with numerical calculation. These geometries are promising for applications such as scanning thermal microscope 26 26. Y. De Wilde, F. Formanek, R. Carminati, B. Gralak, P. A. Lemoine, K. Joulain, J. P. Mulet, Y. Chen, and J. J. Greffet, Nature 444 , 740– 743 (2006). https://doi.org/10.1038/nature05265 and cooling of nanostructures, 21 21. B. Guha, C. Otey, C. B. Poitras, S. Fan, and M. Lipson, Nano Lett. 12 , 4546 (2012). https://doi.org/10.1021/nl301708e but they are not suitable to directly demonstrate large heat flux and spectral coherence. The heat transfer coefficient through the sphere-plate 19 19. E. Rousseau, A. Siria, G. Jourdan, S. Volz, F. Comin, J. Chevrier, and J.-J. Greffet, Nat. Photonics 3 , 514 (2009). https://doi.org/10.1038/nphoton.2009.144 is shown in Fig. 1 after normalizing the result with respect to the sphere area projected to the plate. The result suggests that the heat transfer between the sphere and the plate is far smaller than the theoretical prediction for the parallel-plate geometry. As for the measurement based on the parallel-plate geometry, gaps larger than 1  μ m have been achieved by positioners, monitoring the gap uniformity by capacitive sensors. 27–30 27. C. M. Hargreaves, Phys. Lett. A 30 , 491 (1969). https://doi.org/10.1016/0375-9601(69)90264-3 28. R. S. Ottens, V. Quetschke, S. Wise, A. A. Alemi, R. Lundock, G. Mueller, D. H. Reitze, D. B. Tanner, and B. F. Whiting, Phys. Rev. Lett. 107 , 014301 (2011). https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.107.014301 29. T. Kralik, P. Hanzelka, V. Musilova, A. Srnka, and M. Zobac, Rev. Sci. Instrum. 82 , 055106 (2011). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.3585985 30. T. Kralik, P. Hanzelka, M. Zobac, V. Musilova, T. Fort, and M. Horak, Phys. Rev. Lett. 109 , 224302 (2012). https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.109.224302 On the other hand, mechanical spacers have been inserted between the plates to maintain the gap. 31–33 31. R. S. DiMatteo, P. Greiff, S. L. Finberg, K. Young-Waithe, H. K. H. Choy, M. M. Masaki, and C. G. Fonstad, Appl. Phys. Lett. 79 , 1894 (2001). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.1400762 32. R. DiMatteo, P. Greiff, D. Seltzer, D. Meulenberg, E. Brown, E. Carlen, K. Kaiser, S. Finberg, H. Nguyen, J. Azarkevich, P. Baldasaro, J. Beausang, L. Danielson, M. Dashiell, D. DePoy, H. Ehsani, W. Topper, K. Rahner, and R. Siergiej, AIP Conf. Proc. 653 , 232 (2003). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.1539379 33. L. Hu, A. Narayanaswamy, X. Chen, and G. Chen, Appl. Phys. Lett. 92 , 133106 (2008). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.2905286 In Ref. 32 32. R. DiMatteo, P. Greiff, D. Seltzer, D. Meulenberg, E. Brown, E. Carlen, K. Kaiser, S. Finberg, H. Nguyen, J. Azarkevich, P. Baldasaro, J. Beausang, L. Danielson, M. Dashiell, D. DePoy, H. Ehsani, W. Topper, K. Rahner, and R. Siergiej, AIP Conf. Proc. 653 , 232 (2003). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.1539379 , tubular spacers were manufactured to form a submicron gap between a silicon heater chip and a photovoltaic diode, but the parallelism of the submicron gap was not monitored.
