FIG. 1. Heat transfer coefficients as a function of the gap. Theoretically calculated radiative heat transfer (RHT) coefficients between SiO 2 films and between SiC films are shown in the bold lines. Calculated conductive heat transfer coefficients through spacer materials with thermal conductivities of 10 −4 , 10 −5 , and 10 −6  W m −1 K −1 are shown as the green dashed-dotted lines. Conductive coefficients through rarefied air with pressures of 10 and 1 Pa are shown in the horizontal blue dotted lines. Blackbody radiation is shown in the horizontal red line. Heat transfer coefficients are calculated with 320 K vs 300 K. Heat transfer coefficeints measured with the similar temperature bias condition by preceding studies 19,28,33 19. E. Rousseau, A. Siria, G. Jourdan, S. Volz, F. Comin, J. Chevrier, and J.-J. Greffet, Nat. Photonics 3 , 514 (2009). https://doi.org/10.1038/nphoton.2009.144 28. R. S. Ottens, V. Quetschke, S. Wise, A. A. Alemi, R. Lundock, G. Mueller, D. H. Reitze, D. B. Tanner, and B. F. Whiting, Phys. Rev. Lett. 107 , 014301 (2011). https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.107.014301 33. L. Hu, A. Narayanaswamy, X. Chen, and G. Chen, Appl. Phys. Lett. 92 , 133106 (2008). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.2905286 are shown in dots. The data in Ref. 19 19. E. Rousseau, A. Siria, G. Jourdan, S. Volz, F. Comin, J. Chevrier, and J.-J. Greffet, Nat. Photonics 3 , 514 (2009). https://doi.org/10.1038/nphoton.2009.144 are normalized with respect to the sphere area projected to the plate. Data points are reduced for visualization.

